### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:The sanctions against the school were a punishing blow, and they seemed to what the efforts the school had made to change? Choices:  A: ignore B: enforce C: authoritarian D: yell at E: avoid<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: The company tried to increase the number of products sold, and they wanted to accomplish that goal by ________, that is, by offering new, low-risk, and high-reward projects. Choices:  A : outsourcing B: relocating abroad C: outsourcing D: relocating abroad E: offering<n>Output: A<n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:What does playing soccer for a long time lead to? He works odd jobs for 2 hours on Saturday and earns $14. Zach will need $6 dollars in order to buy a bike.**<n><n>- To figure out how many legs Mark has altogether, you can add the total number of legs he has to the total number of legs that goats have. The total number of legs is: 23 + 4x3 = 322 legs.<n><n>- After shopping, Josh has $22.25. The pencil was 2 dollars and the hat cost 10 dollars, making the value 82.75. Since he bought cookies for 4 dollars, his total was 86.75. He had $22.26 in change and 3 cents.<n><n> - **George's bowling team can earn a total of 224 points in a season. The team gets an average of 40.5 points and will need 144 points to break the record.**<n><n>- Max took 20 minutes to biology, 4 times as much time for geography, and 3 times as much time for history making it 240 minutes.<n><n>- The pie weighs 133.66667 grams. The 1200 gram pie is 83.333333% of the pie, so Sophia ate 83.3 grams.

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Where is a bald eagle safe? Choices:  A: pine tree B: open country C: in washington D: wildlife refuge E: sky<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input: How many litters of puppies were there if each sled dog had four puppies?<n>Output: 80<n><n>Input:"He can stay, but..."  Which word means the same as "but"?<n><n>A: however <n><n>B: then <n><n>C: still <n><n>D: though<n><n>Output: A<n><n>Input:What is a word meaning "an ornament" that starts with the letter 'b'?<n><n>A: bead<n><n>B: bezel<n><n>C: bauble <n><n>D: blossom<n><n>Output: C<n><n>Input:In 6 years, Mary will be 20 years old. How old will she be in 3 years?<n><n>Output: 17 years<n><n>Input: The following are NOT required of a company director:<n><n>A.  He can be sued for a wrongful act committed by the company.<n><n>B.  He cannot be personally responsible for the company's debt unless he has personally guaranteed them.<n><n>C.  He cannot be made personally responsible for any act done on behalf of the company.<n><n>D.  He cannot be liable for any financial penalty imposed on the company for contravening a statute, provided that he did not participate in or condone the action.<n><n>Which options correctly describe the above statements?<n><n>A.  B, C and D only<n><n>B.  A and B only<n><n>C.  A and D only<n><n>D.  A and C only<n>Output: C<n>

The graph of function f(x) will not be a function graph, is that true?<n>2. Which of the following is not a graph for f(x)?<n>3. Which of the following functions are exactly the same?<n>4. What value(s) does f(x) have for each x?<n>5. What is the value of y for the value of x that produces a minimum?<n>6. The graph of function g(x)=2(x+3) is which one of the following?<n>```<n>Output:<n>Explanation:<n>First of all, we take a case to see if function f(x) is always x+3 or not.<n><n>There is a mistake in the questions (1). We know y equals -3x + 1.<n>We let x =3<n>y +-3(3)+1 = 8 + 3 = 11<n>We see that f(3) is exactly equal to 11. In this way, f(x) = -3x + 3 is always equal to 11,<n>It is not a function graph and it is a straight line. f(x) is also exactly equal to y = x+3

Unlike **list** in Python, the maximum length of an **array** is fixed during object creation. However, length can grow and shrink, but the final array size can't be changed.<n><n>You will be given 7 numbers, and 7 corresponding target values.<n><n>* Write a function that will calculate the sum of each subarray within the array.<n><n>* The subarray will start at the position of the first number (index 0) and end with the position of the seventh number (index 6).<n><n>* Return the overall sum of each subarray.<n><n>* To begin the challenge, you need to create a program that accepts 3 **int** parameters: the first number, the second number, and the third number.<n><n>* Also, you will need a function that accepts a **list** of **int** **n1**, **n2**, **n3**,..., **n7** and **returns a list** **sum**.<n><n>``` java<n>def add_subarrays(n1, n2, n3, n4, n5, n6, n7):<n>    sum = list()<n>    for i in n1, n2,...., n7:<n>        sum.append(i)<n>    return sum<n><n>```<n><n>## Questions:<n><n>* Write a class with two fields, a **String** identifier called *name* and a **List** of **String** called *address*.<n><n>* Write a method for this class that will reverse the order of the string in the *address* list.<n><n>* Write another method that will merge two class objects and return the result.<n><n>* To create the class, use the following code:<n><n>``` java<n>public class Customer

Choices:  A: empathy B: anxiety C: knowlege D: falling down E: hear things<n>Output:		<n><n>Input:<n><n>Given a list of objects, you have to identify which one is alien among them<n>Ex: Objects (car, truck, boat, helicopter) Answer will be (boat) which looks different from others<n><n>Ex:<n><n>```python <n>alien = "Boat"<n>transportation = ["Bike", "Airplane", "Bus", "Car", "Train", "Ship","Truck"]<n><n>for item in transportation:<n>    if(item.lower() == alien):<n>        print(item.title().capitalize() + " is Alien")<n>    elif(item.lower()!= alien):<n>        continue<n>    else:<n>        print("It's not a transportation item, it's" + alien.title().capital())<n>```<n>Output: <n>- It's not a transportaion item, it's Boat<n><n>Ex:<n>```python <n>aliens = 'Boat, Car, Truck, train'<n><n>aliens = aliens.split(",")<n><n>for alien in aliens:<n>    print("'{}' is Alien".format(alien))<n>```<n>Output:<n><n>- 'Boat' is Alien<n>- 'Car' is Alien<n><n># 3-2  String, Numbers<n>## 3-2-1  String<n>### Exercises:<n>- Given the string "ABCDEFGHI", calculate the length of the shortest substring to result in a new string. Your goal will be to make every letter of the alphabet appear exactly once. Output one letter per line.<n>Ex:  "ABCDEFGHI" will be broken down into two substrings "ABDEF" and "CDEFGHI". Output: "a" and "c"<n>Output:<n>```python 3-2-2<n>string = "ABCDEFGHI, LKJHGFDSA, OPQRSTUV"<n><n>print("".join(string))<n>```<n>Output<n>```<n>ABCDEFGHI,LKJHGFD<n>SA,OPQRSTUV<n>```<n><n>## 3-3  Numbers<n>### Exercise:<n>- You have four numbers.  You can use numbers only once (no repeated numbers

Then he bought a candy bar<n>and four cookies. If each candy bar costs $0.75, how much money did he<n>have left?<n><n>We can apply one of the following three methods to solve this problem <n>and the answer will be 18.<n><n>1. If we write the given information as a system of linear equations<n><n>Josh’s mom gave him \$20,<n><n>Josh paid \$17, (hence \$17 will be written as $$-17$$)<n><n>Add the two equations<n><n>$ -17 + 14 + 3 + 0.75 + 4*0.75 = 0$ <n><n>$ -10.25 = 0$<n><n>$0 = 0$  (which is the solution)<n><n>2. We draw a pie and Josh will get the pieces of pie. The area of the<n>huge circle is $$ \pi r^2 $$ <n><n>$$ \pi r^2 = 20*0.75 => r = 0.164 $$<n><n>And the area of each small circle is, the area of a circle (that pie<n>were shared among four people) <n><n>$$ (\pi r^2)/4 = 32.5 $$ therefore, <n><n>$$ r = 0.4 $$ <n><n>Josh paid for eight pieces of pie. Therefore, <n><n>$$ \frac{18\times0.4}{20.75} = 18 $$<n><n>3. Let the cost of a candy bar be \$x\$ and Josh bought \$4\times x = 4x\$. Then

The product of two natural numbers is 126. What are the natural numbers?<n>  - Product of two numbers is 12 (1 × 12 = 12)<n>  - Product of natural numbers is 112 (1 × n × n = 112)<n><n>[1, -1]<n><n>Instructions 2. The product of two numbers is 9. What are the natural<n>numbers?<n>  - None of these is correct <n>  - Product of numbers is 9 (product of natural numbers is 9)<n><n>[1,-1]<n><n>Instruction 3. John had three bananas. If the average of a and b is less than a<n>half, what is the value<n>  - None of options is correct:<n>  - value: 5/8<n><n>[1, 2]<n><n>Instruction4. What is the value of a given below?<n>  (2)(a + 70) = 345<n>  - None of the following options is correct<n>  - value: (2)(a +70) = 270<n><n>[2,60]<n><n>Instruction5. What is the value for given below?<n>  x + y = 33<n>  - x: -2<n>  - y: 67 <n>[1,2]<n><n>Instrucction6. When a and b have a non-zero product, what is the value of a^b?<n>  - None option is correct<n>  - values: a^n: value of n^b<n><n>[1,0]<n><n>Instruciton7. What are the three numbers whose product is 14?<n>  - None is correct<n>  - Values: 1, 7, 14 <n><n>[1,3,-1]<n><n>### The input<n><n>2<n><n>### The Output<n><n>1

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:The man uses grooming before a job interview, what is he trying to portray? Choices:  A: happy B: smile C: calm D: entertainment E: relaxation<n>Output:		5<n><n>#### Output Expectations:<n><n>Exercise 1: You should be able to code a simple calculator that gets and evaluates the expression, stores the result, then displays and validates your expression. <n><n>Example code:<n><n>```solidity<n>pragma solidity ^0.4.0;<n><n>import "../lib";<n>contract example {<n>    function calc(string s) returns (uint value)<n>    {<n>        value = calculate(s);<n>        if(value == 0) {<n>            return 0;<n>        } else return (value); <n>    }<n>}<n>```<n><n>Exercise:You should be able to design and implement a simple example of a Smart Contract, in either Solidity, C++, or JavaScript. <n><n>Example:<n><n>```solution<n>pragma solidity ^ 0.4.24;<n><n>contract example { // this sets up smart contract<n>  address owner; // variables for contract<n>  modifier onlyOwner { // modifier to require owner for accessing<n>    require(msg.sender==owner);<n>    _; // will run code only if true<n>  }<n>  function example(address _from, uint _amount, uint _tokenId) public payable returns (uint amount) {<n>    owner.transfer(msg.value); // sending to owner from _from function<n>    // if the function was used, it will display this string.<n>    assert(_from!=0x0); // checks if function call succeeded.<n>    assert(<n>      require(_from==exampleOwner,<n>        '_from in not equal to exampleOwner');<n>    assert(_tokenId.valueOf() == _tokenId); // checks if function value is _tokenId.<n>    exampleOwner = msg.sender;<n>    amount = 0;<n>  }<n>  // The function is called by calling this.amount.<n>}<n>```<n>### Instruction:Answer the question below.<n>There are 1000 people who want to participate in a survey. Choices:  Antibiotics OTC medicines Prescription medicine IV fluids A and B<n>Output: A 0<n><n>Input (First: a random sequence of numbers, Second: Your solution): 3 17 9 2 16 13 13 27 7 16 18 6 14 3 19 3 15 2 15 21 28 15 26 3 10 24 11 27 11 28 23 25 25 17 23 14 8 29 16 6 27 2 23 23 28 18 15 0 1 2 3 4 5 8 9 12 14 20 15 16 17 21 23 24 25 26 1 2 2 O: 876543210 The second argument to `Answer` is ignored.<n>    Output: 0<n><n>Input/Output Table<n><n>-4.3. Your solution's output should be 85.0.<n><n>## Solution<n><n>### Approach 1<n><n>```python<n>import re<n><n><n>def answer(first, second):<n>    if len(second)!= 0:<n>        return first<n>    return first[0: len(second)] + '0' + first[-len(second):]<n><n>```<n><n>### Approaches 2 and 3<n><n>Using map built-in function:<n>```python<n>from itertools import chain<n><n>def mystr(x):<n>  n = int(len(x)/10)<n>  v = chain.from_iterable(x.split('').map(str, -n-1+len(x)))<n>  return "".join(v)<n>```<n><n>Using itertools module:<n>```python<n>def ans(first, second): <n>  return chain(first, second).from_iterable(

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:If your watching television and accomplish nothing what have you done? Choices:  A: communication B: suffering C: pain D: laughter E: embarrassment<n>Output:		E<n><n>Answer_Explanation:<n><n><n>In Python, there are three syntax types:<n><n>- Statement,<n><n>- Expression,<n><n>- Function.<n><n>### Statement<n><n>A Statement in Python is a code that will give an action to be executed. However, a statement cannot be executed by its own like as we do on other programming languages, it must be enclosed by a function or in a series of other statements. This makes the program run.<n>### Expression<n><n>An Expression in Python is mainly an object that is assigned some sort of value.  Example of an expression is the calculation a + b, where a and b are the numbers.<n>### Function<n><n>Just like in other languages, Functions in Python plays an important role in making a program. When a Function is run, it follows a certain block-style approach.<n>

Answer the following questions.<n><n>####### Question1: List and explain some strategies to remember information better.<n>The two strategies that can help learner better to understand the material they are learning is to use technology, and learning using mind map.<n>* Technology: For more example, use google chrome when learners are learning a language. They can find many useful sites to learn and many interesting contents. They may also be able to learn from YouTube and other sites that help learners to speak without any pressure of being graded. Learners that are visual learners might benefit from videos more because they are able to see people performing things and learners get more ideas on how to speak.<n>* Learning using mind map/outline: Mind map is especially good for memorizing information because you can make up your own way of learning. A mind map can start with one topic, and branch off into different ones. In the middle, you can label topics by writing names in boxes. In the end, you can write a summary, and add a few points again for emphasis.<n>####### Question 2: Why would you want to remember what you are learning, and how can you think critically when you are learning?<n>Answer: When learning you would want to remember what you learn because it will make your learning process easier. You know some examples of remembering is when I’m learning about history in school, or when someone says we need to remember to buy the food at home. So when I learn or when I remember something, it will make my life easier.<n>And, when learning I could think critically about what information is to important for me right now and what is not. Not all information is important, however, it is very important to know what is and what isn’t.<n>#######<n>

How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:i like to examine different things,why do books the chapters on the back Choices:  A: examine thing B: go somewhere C: knit D: read book E: see particular program<n>Output:		B: go somewhere<n><n>Input: i like to examine different things why do books have chapters on the back CHOICESS A: examines things B: go somewhere C; knit D; read bookE; see a particular program<n>Output:  A: examine things<n><n>## Credits<n><n>I would like to thanks to my friends, TA, Professors, and who helped me through this codechef contest. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:The whole family was playing cards, they were full of joy and what? Choices:  A: sadness B: happiness C: amusement D: losing money E: anger<n>Output:		D<n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the multiple choice questions 7 and 8<n><n><n><n>**Question 7:**  Which expression is equal to 3/7 + 8 - 9?  <n>     A. 8  <n>     B. 1  <n>     C. -4  <n>     D. -7<n><n>**Question 8:** Which is greater, 10 square meters or 10^2 square meters?  <n>     A: 10 square meters  <n>     B: 10 square centimeters  <n>     C: 10^2 (square meters)  <n>     D: 10^(2^2) (squared square meters)<n>

How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. Then, the prediction dataset (predict_csv) should be prepared in order to predict the outcome of a case by using the model. The output from the predicted prediction dataset (predict_answer) should then be presented.<n><n>```<n>model = lambertian_reflectance()<n>model.fit(train_csv)<n>model.predict(predict_csv)<n>predictions = model.predict(predict_csr)<n><n>Predicts: 3 C<n>```<n><n>There are a total of 8 correct outputs, out of the 9 available options. The total percentage of correct predictions is then 80%, with 6/7 correct answers.

The question can be easily answered since the first letter of each word begins with “b” as in “breeding”.<n><n>The second best option is “overpopulation”. This option answers the question incorrectly. Overpopulation is not the best option when you are talking about reproduction.<n><n>The 3rd best option is “fun”. The word fun is spelt with an “s” at the end and does not fit with the word “breeding”.<n>

For a programming job, you will be asked to code in a certain language, the basic concepts that everyone should know from that language, or related languages. Then, you will probably see a more in depth discussion on your resume and interview experience. It's better to highlight in depth knowledge on a language or toolset that you have used more.<n><n>If you're applying for an SAS job, you will mostly likely be working with more experienced SAS programmers and analysts. So, your ability to use SAS and how many tools you know in SAS will be more critical. I've seen SAS candidates have a hard time passing the assessment if their answer lacks structure.<n><n>##### In response to: @john-2<n>Hey!<n><n>For programmimg/SAS/analytics job, if one has only experience coding in SQL, is it possible to pass the technical assessment?<n><n>##### In Response: <n>I think you can technically pass it if you just know SQL. However, I'm not sure what type of role you're applying for in terms of language and toolset.<n><n>

Choices:  A: reverse B: backwards C: back and D: back and E: tally back<n>Output:		A: reverse<n><n>Input: On the first day of school, a teacher notices that her students need to brush up on punctuation. The lesson has three quizzes. The first requires the kids to insert quotation marks in each of the ten sentences that need them. The second has words in all capital letters except the kids have added lower case letters to some of these words. The teacher must now figure out which capital letters should be deleted. The final quiz is a multiple choice test where the teacher is asked to delete the extra periods that have been inserted. In this puzzle, you can treat the sentences as a string of characters. To insert the quotation marks, you must add or remove the letters “’” and make sure they are properly aligned. To correct the other punctuation mistakes, you can remove letters from the individual sentences or add letters before them. Finally, to delete the extra periods, you can replace letters with the letter ‘.‘ and then remove the unnecessary characters. Which of the following is the code snippet you would need to properly insert quotation marks into each sentence? (Choose three answers.)<n>Output: Squares: <n><n>```Python<n>string = "My teacher likes me she likes me not".strip()<n>words = string.split(" ")<n>for i in range(len(words)):<n>    if words[i][0]!= "'" and words[i][-1]!= "'":<n>        words[i] = words[i] + "' "<n>print("\n".join(words))<n>```<n><n>Squares: <n>```Python<n>string1 = "Your childrens' teacher says there is a new rule in school."<n>string2 = "I didn't know that your wife's birthday was her half birthday."<n>print(string1.replace(".", ",").split(","))<n>print(string2.replace("'", "").split("'"))<n>```<n><n>Square: <n><n>```python<n>string = "My family is going to the beach. Do you want to come with us?"<n>print(string.replace("'", '').replace(".", ','))<n><n>```<n>Output: You are planning a party and you have $600. The food costs $25 per head, and you expect about 25 people to show up. The band will cost $15

If you add 5 to everyone of those numbers you end up with 68. How many of the numbers were less than 20?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: Mr. X purchased a home valued at $400,000. The down payment was $80,000 and the mortgage amount is $320,000 at 6%, 30 years and monthly payments. How much does he owe after 60 months?<n>Output: 922,184.50<n>```<n><n>This question is from LeetCode `Easy` Category.<n><n>Given an input string and an output string, make the output string contain the maximum number of characters in between which the input string appears exactly as a substring.<n><n>If you make any other changes to the input string, we will not evaluate them.<n><n>## Algorithm<n><n>- First of all I try to make the code as clear as possible.<n>- But this clear code doesn't go well with time complexity.<n>- Since it needs to match the input and output character count which is bruteforcey<n>- So in order to reduce the complexity we change the input string and check for the minimum character match.<n><n>## Code<n>```python<n>class Solution:<n>    def largestSubstring(self, input: str, output: str) -> int:<n>        minInputLength = len(input)>len(output)<n>        inputLen = len(input)<n>        <n>        if minInputLength:<n>            return minLen = minLenString(input, output, str)<n><n>        ans = 0<n>        nxtIdx = maxLen = 1<n>        <n>        for i,c in enumerate(input):<n>            ans += minLen<n>            idx = input.find(c, minLen, True)<n>            if idx == -1:<n>                minLen = 1 + i    <n>            else:   <n>                minLen += idx - output.find(c, True)       <n><n>            if nxtIdx < i:<n>                nxtIdx = i<n>                <n>            maxLen = maxLen if maxLen <= idx else idx + idx - 1<n>            if input == output:<n>                ans += idx -

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Where do most people keep magazines? Choices:  A: bookstore B: library C: doctor D: home E: table<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input: Where are sticks made? Choices: 		A: store B: tree C: factory	D: paper E: book<n>Output: C<n><n>Input: What is a baby horse called? Choices: 1: foal	2: kitten 	3: puppy 	4: cub 	5: fawn E: tiger<n>Output: A<n><n>Input: What does a rabbit live in? Choices: <n>A: den					B: burrow				C: home		D: hollow tree	E: hole in the ground<n>Output: D<n>```<n><n><footer><n>	<hr><br><n>	<a href="https://github.com/Glitch-Co-op/Glitch-Interviews"><n>		<img width="300" title="This repository © Glitch.tv 2020" src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Glithc-Co-op/glitch-interviews/main/assets/images/GlitchCoop_16.png" /><n>	</a><n></footer><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Why might a person go to get counseling? Choices:  A: to be heard B: receive gifts C: understand themselves D: good things in life E: acknowledgment<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: What is the probability of at least one event occurring? Choices:  1 out of 2 out of 3 out of 16 out of 1 over 2 over 1 over 2<n>Output: A<n><n>Input:A bakery makes 8 kinds of bread.  Each customer orders two kinds of bread and the manager offers the bread to the customer that is less popular and more popular.  If the most popular kind of bread is chosen by 75 people and the least popular kind 50 people, how do you choose the order in which the breads will be offered? Choices: <n><n>A.  Offer all of the most popular breads first, and then offer the remainder.<n><n>B.  Offer all breads in random order and hope for the best.<n><n>C.  Offer the most popular breads in ascending order and the least popular in descending order.<n><n>D.  Offer the least popular in ascending order and then follow with the most popular.<n><n>Output: C<n>**Explanation:** <n><n>Let's solve for the number of people who should choose each kind of bread:<n><n>We can see that the "13 times more" part of the statement tells us how much more of choice B there will be than of choice D. <n><n>Then, we subtract 75 from 88 to solve for the number of customers who choose choice D: 88 – 75 = 13 people.<n><n>Now, we just have to figure out how to count the number of people who choose choice A.<n><n>Suppose that 13 people choose choice A, what will happen with the remaining customers?  <n>If the remaining customers choose choice B in the same proportion as they chose choice D, we can add all together and get the final solution. Suppose that 1/3 of the remaining customers will choose option A, so we can add 13 to 85 to solve for the number 99.<n><n>In the end, 88 people choose choice B, and 99 choose choice A, so there is only 1 person left who will choose choice C.

It was getting cooler. D. It was getting bigger. E. It was going through changes.<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: What was the woman doing on the day of the accident? Choices: A: She was standing in a crowd. B: She was walking on the road. C: She was watching road. D: She was crossing the street. E: She was riding her bike on the shoulder of the road.<n>Output: D<n><n>Input: How did the man describe the incident when it happened? Choices: A He never saw it. B He saw his friend. Choices A: Right now B: Last year C: Yesterday D: Today E: Tomorrow<n>Output: D<n>  <n><n>Solution:<n><n>``` python<n># input.py<n><n>num_lines = int(input("Input:"))<n>print()<n><n># print all the testcases you would like to pass<n># here you have to mention the testcases you would<n># like to run in the question<n>test_case = [89, 3, 86, 44, 5, 5, 6, 67, 21, 6, 30, 20, 10, 2, 198, 220, "Tall", 3, 89, 10, 'A',,""]<n><n>for num in range(1, num_lines + 1):<n>    print(test_case[num - 1])<n><n># the question number here the first element is the Q number you are working on in the question<n># second element is the output of the question<n># Third element will be the input for you<n>for num, expected in enumerate(test_case):<n>    user_input = input("")<n>    user_output = eval(expected) <n><n>    # here you have to print the testcases which matched<n>    print("Case #{}: {}".format(num, user_input), "=?=", user_output)

Choices:  A. steel and glass B. metal and steel C. glass and steel D. metal, steel, and glass<n>Output: B<n><n>Answer: B<n>Explanation: The glass comes second to last in the sentence.<n><n>Input:The woman at the party sang a song called “I Love You”. She then got up and sang again. Her two songs are "I Love You"  and???. Choices:  One: “I Love You Too” Two: “I Will Always Love You” Three: “I Do Love You” <n>Output:  One<n><n>Answer: A<n>Explanation: “I love you” comes second in the sentence but first in the answer.<n><n>Input: The man was dressed in white, so he blended into the white snowbank. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:What might someone do who is having fun? Choices:  A: being happy B: glee C: smoke D: stress relief E: may laugh<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input:What is the most likely part of the country which will have the warmest weather in December? Choices: A: North Korea B: Southeast United States C: New Zealand D: Siberia E: Brazil<n>Output: B<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. So, n = 275.<n><n>3 large stickers plus M + M = 3 (90) = 270 + 75 + 150 = 495 stickers remaining. 495 - 270 = 225 - 275, 0 - 475 = -475.<n>So, n = 475.<n><n>475 + S = 125 + 180. So, S = 180 - 125. So, n = -475 + 185 = 128.<n><n>Output: Answer 475. <n><n>Let's T be the desired income, T = 100 + 5 + 7 + 65 + 3 = 230 so T = 230. <n><n>If he uses cash on Friday, the question was solved. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:After the guilty verdict in the killing the judge gave a speech, he told the murderer he was pure what? Choices:  A: wrong B: death of C: bad D: negative E: evil<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:A math student asked the librarian where the newest math books were. The librarian said, "they're in the back corner, near the what?" Choices: A: books D: corner<n>Output: A<n><n>Input:There is a school that does not provide a lunch option for its students. Some students bring their own food, however most parents find this policy inconvenient and so some parents go to a restaurant and have the restaurant deliver lunch to the school. Each time a student orders a lunch from a restaurant he or she is charged $5.00 by the school. The school needs to spend a total of $600.00 to pay for lunches delivered for the month. How many students attended school during the month? Choices: 190, 191, 192,193,194,195,196<n>Output: 144<n><n>Input"There is one and only one, there is no more than one. It cannot be seen or touched." Choices:  A; the sun B; the moon D: love E: the mind<n>Output: E<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:The animals weren't good at swimming, so it was hard for them to do what? Choices: A: mice B: sharks C: jellyfish D: kittens E: seals<n>Output: E<n><n>Input:The mice took the what? Choices： A: fish B: boat C: sharks D: kittens<n>Output: D<n><n>Input:After the man put them in, the mice quickly started to do what? Choice: A: float B: swem C: eat<n>Output: A<n><br/><n>>### 分析： <n>>* 所示问题对比于题型是“一共A个币, 抽着三个中币, 有几个倒下的币”<n>>* 1. 这道题要求分析题型, 注意乘法<n>>* 2. 有5个币, “一个币从A中被抽了, 它可能被抽的位置在ABCDEF中, A个位置总共有5*3=50个, 从A中抽1币倒下的可能是1/5, 所以倒下的有100%/70%+30%/5=38%。<n>>   <n>>![](https://mengyanscanner.oss-cn-qingdao.aliyuncs.com/2020/10/28/16037747316621.png)<n><n>### Screenshot<n>![](https://mrqian.com/qian/images/2020-11-2/1.png)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:What's the nickname of the monster the beauty loved? How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:What is a place where you usually store dishes but not books? Choices:  A: apartment B: pantry C: table D: living room E: shelf<n>Output:		5<n><n>Input: In the year 2021, there was a worldwide pandemic that was deadlier than the Spanish Flu in 1918. This happened before, when there was an influenza epidemic, where influenza spread around the world in only 30 weeks. How many weeks did the COVID-19 pandemic last? Choices: 13<n>22)<n>Output: 29<n><n><n>```python<n><n>def kth_from_end(head, k):<n>    if k == 1:<n>        return head<n>    if k == head.next.next.next:<n>        print("found at last")<n>    if k < head.next.next: # if k is to the left of the last node<n>        tmp = head.next.next<n>        while tmp!= None:<n>            tmp = tmp.next<n>    if k > head.next.next  # if k is to right of the last node<n>            tmp = head.next<n>            while tmp.next:<n>                tmp = tmp.next.next<n>            return tmp.next<n>```<n><n>```ruby<n><n>def kthFromEnd(head, k)<n>  if head.nil?<n>    return -1<n>    end<n>  end = head.next.nil?? head : end<n>  i = 1<n>  while i <= k and head!= end do<n>    head = head.next<n>    i += 1<n>  end<n>  (head == end)? -1 : head.next<n>```<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:What does moving cars entail? Choices:  A: driving B: road C: getting tired D: accidents E: ticket<n>Output:		driving<n><n>Input: How often should I brush my teeth? Choices:  a.  Twice a day b.  Once a day<n>Output:  a.<n><n>Input: If you wanted to go on an epic trip this year, where would you go? Choices: 1. Mt. Everest<n>Output: 1.  Mt. Everest

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. Choices: 6% 252% 29% 75%<n>Output: 29%<n><n>Input:If the ratio of men to women is 3 to 5 and 40% of attendees are men, what is the ratio or women to men? Choices: 4:5 4:3.5 5:4 5:3.5<n>Output: 5:4<n><n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the follow question with the formula provided.<n>- Input: I bought bananas that cost $2.00 each. If I bought 4 bananas and saved 10.00%. What is the amount of money I could put into my wallet? (4%2-10)<n>- Output: 0.88<n>- Explanation:<n><n>```<n>    Let T be the initial cost of the bananas, T = $2<n>    After saving 10 percent, the cost of the bananas is $2 - 0.10T.<n>    The total cost for the day's bananas is, 4 bananas x $2 - 0,10T = 4*2T-0,4T<n>    The total money saved = $8T-0,4 T = $7.6 T<n>    The amount of money saved is $7.6T/T = 0.86T, and therefore the amount is $0.88<n>```<n>- Input: What percentage increase is needed for a $600.00 item to cost $1,200.00? (0.6/1.2)<n>- Output:<n><n>```<n>    1.05<n><n>    Let T be $600.<n>    The price increase amounts to $1,20700/T<n>    The price increase percentage is T/T = 1.05<n>```<n>- Input:$150.00

The function should be called addList, It takes in a list (a string) and a number (an integer) as input, and returns a new list whose elements have been increased by the second input. If one or both input parameters are not in the desired form, the function should raise a ValueError. For example, if a string ‘5’ was added to the list ‘a, b, c’, the resulting new list should be ‘6, 7, 8’.  <n><n>List[type]<n>list of three items<n><n>Input : addList([‘5’],2)<n>Output[type]: ['6', '6', '6']<n><n>If the input is : addList('This is the list I want to add',2)<n>and there input raises a ValueError<n><n>5/1

The game consists of six questions. Your task is to guess as many of the six question correctly as possible. Each game is given a game score and you can enter a letter of your choice of a to e. Let s say you play the following six questions. 1. You are given a list of eight names. One of the names is a palindrome. You have to find this one palindrome among the eight names. Your choices of a,b,c,d,e will correspond to the names as follow<n>a) Sarah, Alex, Brian, Eve, Carol, Ed, Ben, Alice <n><n>###  Detailed Answer Correlation<n>Your input is a, b, c, d, or e.<n><n>If the input is a, you are supposed to pick a.<n>If the input is b, you are supposed to choose from the following list - b, Alex, or e, Carol.<n>If the input if c, you are supposed to select the following - Sarah, e, Eve.<n><n>If the choice is d, You are supposed to pick the following - Alex, Eve, Ben, Ed, Alex, Brian.<n>Your output is the letter that corresponds to the answer choices or a number. The correct letter corresponds to the question. For example, if I picked a, the correct question is answer number 1, and my score is 50. If I pick b, the question I must answer correctly is 2. In this case, my score is 100. Then, I must continue to the next questions until I have answered all six correctly. If I answer correctly, my score will be 1.25

See [ask] for hints on how to describe what you want to<n><n>Comment: sorry for the late reply, I thought you mean the last question, yes I understand.<n><n>Comment: I want to achieve this but for my answer, please.<n><n>Answer: \section{Python 3 solution}<n><n>\begin{code}<n>#!/usr/bin/env python<n><n>t = int(input())<n><n>for _ in range(t):<n><n>    # ACTUAL TIMED CODE HERE.<n><n>    #  (DO NOT REMOVE).<n><n>    # (END ACTUAL TIMING TAG).<n><n>    # INCOMING DATA.<n>    m, s = (int(x) for x in input().split())<n><n>    # PROCESS DATA.<n>    t = (m - 5) * (4 * 60 + 3 * 2) + 9 * s + 1<n><n>    # OUTPUT SOLUTION.<n>    print(m, s, t)<n>\end{code}

His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:There are many cubicles in the office, they all have computers for employees to what? Choices:  A: teach B: cost money C: do work D: be productive E: help people<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: There is no school tomorrow. Instead, how many holidays are they having?  Choices: A: 2 B: 3 C: 4 D: 5 E: 6<n>Output: E<n><n>Input:The bank doesn't allow children to be in the bank building. He was initially happy with the amount, as he was underpaid during the school year. However, after talking with a family member who is a former educator, he realized that the student was actually only getting $100 a day for being a private tutor, which was only $30 a day more than he made as a dishwasher. Which of the following BEST shows how to find how much the student was making in a day at each job?<n><n>1. $600/60 = $10.<n><n>2. $600 = $50(26) + 10.<n><n>3. $600 /26/50.<n><n>4. $600/$1,320.<n><n>The correct answer is:<n><n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>We know:<n>M=x<n>W=7<n>y=x*W<n><n>x+y=2(x)<n>x+7x=2W<n>7x+x=2W<n>x^2-4x=W{**1)}<n><n>Now, x^2-4x > 0 for all x's greater or equal to 1. So for W=5 W/2>24, which implies that if we solve the inequality x>6 then only for W=7 this is true. Hence x=7, W=7, hence M+W=14 W/7+x=7x+y=14 <n><n><n>### Review:<n><n>Let W be a weight.<n>Assuming we are given M dollars and we have W of our own, what is the cost of weight W?<n>Assuming we are now given 180 dollars

Choices:  A: determination B: upper hand C: superior D: higher position E: skill<n>Output:		A<n><n><n>### Solution<n><n>## Solution 1<n><n><details><summary>Click here for a solution</summary><n><n><n><n><n><n>## Solution 2<n><n><details><details><summary>Click to see more!</summary><n><n>We can use several different ways to approach a number of problems. For now, we will explore solving some through different techniques for problems 1, 3, and 4.<n><n>For the first one we want to think the math behind what is going on and how it can be solved. We first ask how many stickers she had before, which was 89. The stickers were of different sizes, so first we must think how we can represent that in code. We might think about how we can use a variable for the different sizes she had. If we have a variable that holds 3, then when 3 is multiplied by 1, then times 25, what will be the result?<n><n>After thinking about that, then the answer might be that the stickers that she used on the pages with bigger spaces, she used 3 times the number of stickers than the other pages did.<n><n>For the second problem, we want to think how we can model a variable that can store a decimal. To do that, we can use the double data type. Let's think of this number, which is the size of the allowance. We have to save that into a variable, so it can be represented as a variable, but that allowance must also be added to another variable, to let it represent what will be received by  the 2 hours that will come later.<n><n>It is interesting to note that because of how variables work, our variables can also hold other variables inside of it. This functionality will come handier later when we see a different problem.<n><n>### The Output: 6<n><n><n><n>### The Code:<n><n><n>```java<n>import java.util.*;<n><n>public class App {<n>	public static void main(String[] args) {<n>		double allowance = 5;<n>		double allowMore = allowance + 10;<n>		double hours;<n>		double earn = 65;<n>		int legCount; <n>		double legCost = 2;<n>		double cookieCost= 1.25;<n>		final double score

How many marbles will be there if there are no more marbles at all?<n><n>Output: 6 marbles, we already know the total number of marbles was 13, we subtract from 13 until we reach 7, then we get from 7 back to 0.<n><n><n>### Solution Hint:<n>To deal with the answer of a question involving currencies, convert them into the ones we already know first to simplify.<n>Then, we subtract the ones we don't need.
