How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:The swimming pool couln't be refilled due to drought regulations, where was it located? Choices:  A: ymca B: california C: park D: first floor E: school<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:A group of teenaged friends were hanging out playing video games and listening to music at one of their friend's homes. One teen liked the new movie in theaters but his friends did not. After two hours, they'd had enough hanging out which of the following would they likely do? Choices:  a. Go see the new movie. b. Go play video games at a friend's house. c. Go play video games in their bedrooms. d. Go listen to music in their bedrooms.<n>Output: d<n><n>Input:I just made a reservation to stay at the ____ Inn. Choices:  A. best B. bad C. worse D. worse<n>Output: B<n><n>Input:What color do you like best? Choices:  pink purple black blue yellow green<n>Output: D<n><n>Input:What time is it? Choices:  midday morning noon<n>Output: A<n><n>Input:The dog likes ___ fruits the most. Choices:  all pineapple grapes banana<n>Output: C<n><n>Input:There was a fire in one part of the kitchen. It was a ____ fire. Choices:  grease fire gas fire microwave fire<n>Output: A<n>

What is the number?<n>Output: 8<n><n>

How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Dave put his beer where he could get to it, but it would be off the floor.  Where did he put it? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: closet C: can D: shelf E: soccer game<n>Output:		c<n><n>Input: The number with only one digit is? Choices: 15 13 11 10<n>Output: b<n><n>Input: Which is the largest rectangle you can draw within the figure? Choices: A B C D E F G<n>Output: f<n><n>Instruction:For this question, we are going to use the following function to represent an integer number. We are going to store the integer number in memory starting from the least significant bit which starts from 000000. So 15 we convert to an array and store in memory as 00001111.<n>The function that does it is :<n>```java<n>function(integer number)<n>{<n> int numberInMemory = 0;   // stores the integer in memory<n> int bitLength = 8; // 8 memory locations for each bit length<n> int currentIndex = 0;<n> <n> boolean isNot0 = false; // checks whethere the bit not zero<n> <n> for(int i = power(2, integer);i>0;i/=2) <n> {<n>  if(number%i==1)<n>  {<n>   addOneInMemory(numberInMemory, bitLength, currentIndex);<n>   currentIndex = currentIndex + bitLength;<n>   isNot0 = true;<n>  }<n> }<n> <n> if(isNot0)<n> {<n>  addOneInMemory( numberInMemory, bitLength-1, currentIndex); //add carry only if last digit is a 1<n>  currentIndex = currentIndex - bitLength +1;<n> }<n> <n> return numberInMemory;<n>}<n>```<n>1. This function will return the memory representation of 20. That number will be stored from the least significant bit to the most significant which is located to the right of it as shown below:<n>A. 0000 0000<n>B. 1101 1001<n>C. 0001 1110<n>D. 1110 10<n><n>Output: A<n><n>Input:This function will return the memory represetation for 24:<n>A. 1111 0000 B. 000 1100 C. 00 1000

Choices:  A: get tired B: have legs C: skip D: not fat E: look first<n>Output:		[B] have legs<n><n>#### [3]<n><n>### Instruction:This section tests the ability to analyze and reason. Read the following description of a scenario and answer the four questions that follow.<n><n>"Alice and Bill are playing a game. For each player to be able to play the game they need 20 coins. In the first round, Alice has 20 coins and gives a coin to Bill. Bill has 10 coins, puts 5 coins into a box, and gives 5 coins to Alice.  The next round, Bill gets 5 coins from the box, puts 4 coins into the box, and brings 4 coins to Alice. The next round, Bill and Alice both put 5 coins into the box. The next round, Alice has 5 coins, puts 1 in the box, and gives 4 coins to Bill. Bill brings 4 coins into Alice. The next round Bill brings 5 coins to an empty box. The final round has 5 coins in the box, Bill gives 3 coins to Alice, and Alice gives one coin to Bill. Who has more coins after the game is over?"<n><n>#### 1. How many rounds was that game played?<n><n>1) 20 rounds<n><n>2) 8 rounds<n><n>3) 9 rounds<n><n><n>#### 2. Did Alice win the game?<n><n>1) Yes<n><n>2) No<n><n>3) It Depends<n><n>#### 3. Who gave more coins to the other player?<n><n>1) Bill<n><n>2) Alice<n><n>3) It is unclear<n><n>#### 4. How many coins were in the box by the end of the game?<n><n>Output: <n>Alice won after playing 8 rounds. Bill donated a total of 29 (5 + 4 + 9 + 5 +4 + 3) coins and Alice donated a total of **23** (5 + 4). Because the box contained 5 coins after the 8th round, Bill donated 29 coins on average per round.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:She was processing the wool, she kept her leg bouncing to operate the what? Choices:  A: hospital bed B: legroom C: spinning wheel D: grand piano E: rhythm<n>Output:		B<n><n># Challenge_08<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the questions below based on the following information (you will be given some basic information, as well as having to identify additional given information, which will help you answer the question).  <n><n>Input: The number of people who attended the workshop. How many students received an A and scored above a 70?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: The following prices per cup are for coffee, tea and cake.<n>Coffee: $25 for a cup and $50 for 4 cups.<n>Tea: $30 for a cup and $90 for 4 cupps.<n>Cake: $20. How many cups of each can I buy for $100? <n>Output: 2 and 1<n><n>Input: The cost of the ingredients, 3 cups of sugar, 4 cups of vegetable oil, 10 cups of flour, and 8 trays, is $72. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Where would you put a computer other than a desk? Choices:  A: apartment B: table C: school D: office E: house<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input: Where would you put a laptop other than a den? How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. This programming language is not only used as a system scripting language, it is also considered as a general purpose programming language.   It is popularly known as a dynamic, object-oriented, interpreted language.  This type of language supports integrated data types and automatic memory management. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Sally took her medicine and experienced strong side effects.  What did doctors say about the side effects? Choices:  A: great B: distinguished C: remarkable D: excellent E: peculiar<n>Output:		 D<n><n><n><n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Where was the apple tree said to contain something forbidden? Choices:  A: north carolina B: washington state C: nil D: great outdoors E: garden of eden<n>Output:		E<n><n>### [Instruction: Answer the following question. Each question is independent and correct response is indicated with the answer.<n>```python<n>>>> (a + b*2 + (c+d)*3)%7<n>2<n>>>> a = "3.14159"<n>>>> int(a[0]) == 3<n>True<n>>>> a == "a"<n>False<n>>>> a == 3<n>False<n>```<n><n>### [instruction: Answer The following question. Write the answer in the input field.<n><n>a = 20<n>b = 70<n>c = 50<n><n>if a is equal to 20<n><n>a is equal to 10<n><n>else<n><n>a is equal 30<n><n>if b is equal to 70<n><n>b is equal to 30<n><n>else do nothing a, print('false')<n>

How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Why would someone confess to committing murder? Choices:  A: gorgeous B: handsome C: pleasing D: glorious E: pretty beautiful<n>Output:		None of the above<n><n>```<n>### Solution:<n><n><n>The first step was to put the statements onto a chart. I was able to determine that the answer keys were: <n><n>- A	*Gorgeous<n>- B	*HANDSOME<n>- C	*GORGEOUS<n>- D	*GLORIOUS<n>- E	*PRETTY BEAUTIFUL<n><n><n>| Statement       | Chart                                             |<n>| ----------------|--------------------------------------------------- |<n>| He finally found someone as ugly...   | He finally found someone as... |<n>| 252             |                                               |<n>| He finally fo... |  he definitely stood  |<n>| 397             |                                              <n><n> 252<n> 397<n><n><n>I made the decision to first determine the longest statement, which was Statement 2. Then, I created a number chart using the following steps (as seen below):<n><n>| Statement 2 (Long) | Number Chart  |<n>| ------------------ | ----------------|<n>| He finally found...  | 118              <n>| He finally found...   | 168             <n>| 118              | 1            <n>| 168              | 2            <n><n>After the number chart was created, I took a close look at the number pattern and found out that the pattern was a geometric sequence. This meant I could use the following formula to determine the answer.<n><n>Number in sequence = a*(1^p)(a<sup>q</sup>)<n><n>The first term in the sequence with p = 5 and q = 5. This meant I found the answer to be: a(1^5)^5 = 2 + 5 * 5^5 = 47, making the answer D, GlRioSuS.<n><n><n><n><n><n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input: Tom's brother is 4 times as old as Tom's dog. If in 6 years, Tom's brother will be 30 years, how old is Tom's dog going to be in six years?<n>Output: 12<n><n>Input: There are 50 children at the party. Three-fifths of them are boys. How many of the children are girls?<n>Output: 20<n><n>Input: Gail has some bills in her wallet which amount to $100. She has four $5 bills and three $20 bills, and the rest are $10 bills. How many $10 bills are in her wallet?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: A 220-liter barrel has a small leak. It lost 10% of its contents before anyone noticed. How many liters are left in the barrel?<n>Output: 198<n><n>Input:Why might someone want to be buying beer? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. In many countries, a small glass of whiskey is the accepted reward. If you are served one ounce of whiskey, you will be served  about 28 ml, and you will be getting a  "wee dram". In what is known as the "little measure", approximately 25 ml of whiskey  is poured, and some like to call it a "nip" or "snifter". You are served another variation when drinking whiskey in Italy, Switzerland, Germany, and Austria.
